<br>
I have had very good experiences lately partnering with a wizard, doing the aggro kiting thing.  In <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>PoP</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, elementals are not much tougher than a pinata, and absent slow, kiting seems to be the way to go.  But as a mage, I don't really have the tools for kiting, and tempermentally, I am more suited for static fights.  A wizard partner has the tools for kiting, and has root and snare to make adds and pet death much more manageable.  The wizard orbits around me, I nuke, the pet chases the mob, and all is well.<br>
<br>
In a group that has met its style minimums <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>(trinity, pet, or kiting)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, a wizard is a very welcome addition.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Razamatazz Pizzazz</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=elasto>Elasto</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Arcanist</span><br>  Posts: 993<br> <font color=#ffffff>(1/29/03 4:15 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Perception of the Wizards groupability.</span><hr size=1> The more I play this game, the more I realise how incredibly difficult balancing is.<br>
<br>
Groups basically need a tank, a healer, a slower and 3 misc damage dealers. Somewhere in there there needs to be some cc, whether it be fd, rooting or whatever.<br>
<br>
If casters always did more considerably more long term damage in groups than melee (which some people advocate due to melee having more ac, hp than casters), then all melee would be fighting for that single tank spot (and pets can take that role at a pinch anyway). That simply would not be reasonable!<br>
<br>
As it is, if uptime is remotely normal casters *do* do more damage than melee. It's only cos people overestimate uptime in the average group (or simply dont understand the concept) that melee are still desirable there atm.<br>
<br>
Melee, in general, cant solo anything like as well as casters either, especially in PoP.<br>
<br>
And, gee, melee are very aware that they are pretty useless on PoP raids compared to the fast damage from casters, though they know they still contribute on Velious and Luclin raids.<br>
<br>
At the moment, therefore, casters are threatening to dominate solo, group and raid!<br>
<br>
Now, post-kunark but pre-focus items melee *did* do too much damage in groups compared to casters, especially wizards. Right now I think the balance is pretty much spot on post-60 for the following reason:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>A higher level damage dealer with a ton of aa and great gear will outdamage a lower level with few aa and poor gear, almost regardless of class.</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> And VI have now made it all but impossible to get max aa and gear; I'd be suprised if even 5% of everyone who ever played achieves it. At it's simplest that's why EQ balance has always worked; you can (almost) never reach the limit of your power, regardless of your class.<br>
<br>
One huge reason why people cant agree on melee/caster and caster/caster balance is because people value utility so very differently.<br>
<br>
To the raid whore, damage is all - utility is meaningless.<br>
To the low risk xp grind whore, utility is useful a little, but not much. Mostly damage is all.<br>
To the soloer or adventurer (and that includes groups that explore dungeons and try hard mobs for fun), utility is almost all. The ability to stun/snare/root/ss/burn/evac makes a wizard tons better than, say, a mage or rogue.<br>
<br>
Again, many casters discount their ability to solo as if it is nothing. We take it completely for granted, yet many classes *cannot* solo in PoP, and we would be p*ssed if our soloing ability got reduced to that of, say, a warrior or rogue! We get annoyed that mages can 'outnuke' us at 61 - do people not realise how annoying it is for a tank to be lfg in a PoP zone and see a wizard or druid quadding (sometimes while lfg, sometimes not)? It isnt our 'birthright' to solo yet we treat it as such and ignore it totally when it's convenient to us on class balance. It *urks* other classes.<br>
<br>
Finally, MOST classes find it no easier to get a group than us.<br>
<br>
Most groups want one cleric, but only one per group. Ditto shaman and chanter. As ac, hp and damage grow over time, the importance of these classes drops. Just remember the state of the game with grinding in Luclin.<br>
<br>
Most groups want one of warrior, paladin or shadow knight. They dont usually want two plate tanks in a group.<br>
<br>
That leaves the other 8 classes chasing 2 or 3 spots, which is an identical proportion to plate tanks with their spot. Out of those 8, no class has such a compelling reason to be picked it excludes all others; it all depends on level, gear, aa and uptime as to who will do more damage. Only a n00b would think otherwise.<br>
<br>
Quite frankly, and this has been said before but is worth saying again, the *only* person that gets a group quickly in this game is the person that starts it.<br>
<br>
Having said all of that, I agree with Noonie that if spell damage were shown it would increase the desirability of casters. Imagine the spam from showing dot damage though ugh <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=elasto>Elasto</A> at: 1/29/03 4:26:10 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=staccatoobligato>Staccato Obligato</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Visitor</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#ffffff>(1/31/03 5:39 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Perceptions of an outsider</span><hr size=1> I think the problem is perception, and the perception is even changing in your favor.<br>
<br>
Pre-PoP, the best groups were AE.  They nerfed AE pulling (when they changed it so you could get hit more than 4 mobs at once).  From that point on, the best groups were the ones that could fight blues non-stop.<br>
<br>
A puller would go get several mobs, the enchanter would mez the extras, then the group would mow through.  As they were killing the last one, the puller would go get more.<br>
<br>
This non-stop pace of battle made manaless damage the most efficient and effective.  Tailored melee groups ruled.  Nuke classes looked bad in comparrison.<br>
<br>
In PoP, we no longer chain-pull.  If a puller routinely comes back with 3 to 5 mobs, you fire him.  Good pullers do everything they can to ensure they arrive with a manageable number ... like 1.<br>
<br>
This gives a pull-pause pace to the fighting.  Casters get a lot more time to med, and this favors the nukers who can &quot;store&quot; damage during downtime and &quot;spend&quot; it during fights.  The slower pace of the kills is more than compensated by the increased XP in PoP.<br>
<br>
In addition, the outdoor zones also favor the casters on horses.  I've heard casters comment that they can't get low on mana, and the only limit to their damage is agro.  (The casters had KEI + horses + Wind of Marr + some FT.)<br>
<br>
Rogues have already started complaining that mages are beating them as damage-dealers in XP groups.  They're worried about what will happen to them when this becomes everyman knowledge.<br>
<br>
Wizards aren't at that level, but they have moved to the point where I lump them in with the mages, rogues, rangers and monks (and beastlords, but I keep forgeting they exist).  I'm pretty close to Frodlin.  I'm taking a damage dealer now, instead of waiting for a different class to show up later.<br>
<br>
Another thing that's changed my feelings toward wizards is the change I've noticed in wizards toward bards.  In the past, wizards were the most notorious offenders in the &quot;mana song plz&quot; category.  I play one of the most challenging classes, and it always annoys me when someone acts like my sole purpose is to service their mana pool.<br>
<br>
In PoP, I've seen a bit different attitude.  Wizards have fallen in love with Rizlona's Call of Flame (aka the focus song).  This has increased their awareness that there are other bard songs that are highly valuable.  Now most wizards seem content to let me work my songs in the manner I see best, even when it means their favorites are excluded in favor of more necessary songs.<br>
<br>
Or maybe I've just been grouping with smarter wizards.<br>
<br>
Elasto, I enjoyed your post; very well thought out.<br>
<br>
-----------------------------------<br>
